{"title_page": "Midori (actress)", "text_new": "{{short description|American pornographic actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Midori\n| image         = Midori db.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Michele \"Midori\" Watley in 2006\n| birth_name    = Michele Watley<ref name=\"Rodeo\">{{cite web|title=Midori Interview|url=http://www.johnrodeo.com/archives/midori.html|publisher=Johnrodeo.com|accessdate=8 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111135610/http://www.johnrodeo.com/archives/midori.html|archivedate=11 November 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1968|07|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], [[North Carolina]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| citizenship = United States\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Singer<br/>Dancer<br/>Model<br/>Actress\n| years_active  = 1989\u2013present\n| known_for     = First African-American woman to win an [[AVN Awards|AVN Award]]\n| notable_works = \n| relatives          = [[Jody Watley]] <small>Sister</small>\n| website = {{url|http://www.midorimusic.net}}\n}}\n\n'''Michele Watley''', better known by her stage name '''Midori''' (born July 19, 1968), is an American singer, dancer, model, actress and former [[pornographic actress]]. She was inducted into the [[AVN Hall of Fame]] in 2009.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\">{{cite web |last1=Lindemulder |first1=Janine |title=Weekendowa Bezsensja: Muzyka 18+, czyli muzyka a bran\u017ca porno (3) |url=https://esensja.pl/muzyka/publicystyka/tekst.html?id=13124&ref=ak_wj |website=Esensja |accessdate=15 January 2020|language=pl}}</ref><ref>[https://avn.com/business/articles/video/2009-avn-award-winners-announced-56551.html 2009 AVN Award-Winners Announced, by David Sullivan] January 11, 2009, [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]</ref> She was the first [[African-American]] woman to win an AVN award, when she was named \"Best Supporting Actress\" in 2001.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> Watley was also named one of the top 10 \"hottest black porn stars\" of all time by ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]'' named her \"the queen of the black hardcore market.\"<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite web |title=The Top 50 Hottest Black Porn Stars Of All Time |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/the-top-50-hottest-black-porn-stars/midori |website=Complex |accessdate=12 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Judah\">{{cite news |last1=Judah |first1=Hettie |title=Interview: Charmaine Sinclair - All glammed out and nowhere to go |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/interview-charmaine-sinclair-all-glammed-out-and-nowhere-to-go-1187977.html |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=The Independent |date=29 November 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622132025/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/interview-charmaine-sinclair-all-glammed-out-and-nowhere-to-go-1187977.html |archivedate=22 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nMichele Watley was born in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. Watley has a brother and a sister. Her sister is [[Jody Watley]]. When Watley was a [[toddler]], her family relocated to [[Kansas City, Missouri]], followed by [[Chicago, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> Her grandfather and father were a ministers.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/><ref name=\"BVI\">\"Makin' It With Midori\". ''Black Video Illustrated'' (10). 1997.</ref><ref name=\"OReilly\">{{cite news |last1=O'Reilly |first1=Finbarr |title=She sings, too |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209551/p_b5/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=The National Post |language=en}}</ref> Her parents divorced when she was twelve, and Watley and her sister, Jody, moved to California. Watley called her childhood \"sheltered\" and that her parent's were \"strict.\" When she was in junior high school, she said she was \"mortified\" seeing girls kissing their boyfriends. Eventually, Watley turned into what she called \"a wild child.\"<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>\n\nAs a teenager, Watley started dancing, performing hip hop, ballet and jazz styles. She studied theater in college and performed in plays.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> As a young adult, she lived in England for nine months and in 1986, she attended dance school in France.<ref name=\"BVI\"/> Watley was also a hair model for [[Vidal Sassoon]], as well as a [[backup singer]] and dancer. As Michele Watley, she acted in commercials and modeled in ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''. She did not pursue modeling full-time, as she was \"not tall enough to be a super model.\"<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>\n\n==Career==\nShe appeared as Michele Watley in [[John Landis]]' classic comedy film starring [[Eddie Murphy]], ''[[Coming to America]]'' (1989), as one of the nude bathroom maidens.<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite news |title=Rock's Most Embarassing Siblings |url=https://www.retrojunk.com/community/post/index/46055 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |issue=41 |date=October 2005 |page=58 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter her role in ''Coming to America'', she changed her stage name to Midori.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/> She worked as an [[exotic dancer]] for four years<ref name=\"BVI\"/> and in 1995<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> she started performing in [[hardcore pornography]]. Her first scene was with [[Jake Steed]].<ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/> She didn't perform in films another year.<ref name=Blender/> Watley's rationale for entering the adult film industry was to increase the representation of women of color in the industry, which has historically been white.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/><ref name=\"OReilly\"/>\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = \"You have the playboy blond, who is sexy and every man's dream, and as an African American woman I was like 'ok, where is the sex symbol that looks like me?' And there were very few, if not any. That made me a little head strong, and I tried to figure out why. And the further I looked into it I thought 'I want to change this, because this isn't right.\"|author = Michele \"Midori\" Watley|source = 2002 interview with John Rodeo<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>|width = 50%|align = right}}\n\nIn the 1990s, Watley began directing pornographic films<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite news |title=Watley's Porn-Again Sister |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30760348/daily_news/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=New York Daily News |date=20 February 1997}}</ref> and started back up singing,<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> including for [[Kid Rock]] in 1999.<ref name=Blender/> She initially tried to avoid appearing in [[Stereotypes of African Americans|stereotypical Black]] themed films and early in her career was mostly featured in [[interracial]] scenes in white produced films. Watley eventually started working with Black male performers because \"didn't want to have Black guys thinking I didn't do them too.\"<ref name=\"TVV\">{{cite news |last1=Suggs |first1=Donald |title=Sex Sells |publisher=The Village Voice |date=21 October 1997 |page=40 |quote=Performers who can't-or won't-cultivate the requisite image end up in a rut of \"amateur\" or low-budget race productions, where they earn as little as $200 a film. \"I didn't want to do any Soul Train booty movies,\" says 29-year-old Midori, aXa the \"Black Barbie Doll;' explaining why she initially didn't pursue Black porn films. \"Those aren't the ones getting adult awards or attention from the mainstream media;' says Midori, who received the Best Newcomer Award at the Atlantic City ceremony. Like most successful women of color in the industry, Midori started by doing interracial scenes in white-produced films. But in a sudden burst of racial consciousness, she went into Black porn. \"I didn't want to have Black guys thinking I didn't do them too,\" she explains.}}</ref> She became an spokesperson for the [[Free Speech Coalition]].<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> She was co-featured, as Michele, in the 1997 stripper documentary ''The Unveiling'', alongside [[Dixie Evans]] and Eldad Sahar.<ref name=\"LATimesUnveiling\">{{cite news |title='The Unveiling': Sure-Fire Subject Has Its Charms |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-03-27-ca-42382-story.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=27 March 1997}}</ref><ref name=\"McCluskey2007\">{{cite book|author=Audrey Thomas McCluskey|title=Frame by Frame III: A Filmography of the African Diasporan Image, 1994-2004|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5qmplifVDIC&pg=PA764|year=2007|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-34829-3|page=764}}</ref><ref name=\"Harvey\">{{cite web |last1=Harvey |first1=Dennis |title=The Unveiling |url=https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/the-unveiling-1200453852/ |website=Variety |accessdate=15 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001172912/https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/the-unveiling-1200453852/ |archivedate=1 October 2016 |language=en |date=29 June 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"LAWeekly\">{{cite news |title=Documentary Days: The Unveiling |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/578490541/ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=Newspapers.com |agency=LA Weekly |date=25 September 1997}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described Watley as \"a petite African-American single mom who does an athletic pole-climbing act.\"<ref name=\"Harvey\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' described Watley as being \"loaded with personality, and you hope that she fulfills her dream of moving into mainstream entertainment as a singer or actress.\"<ref name=\"LATimesUnveiling\"/>\n\nIn 1997, she recorded a duet with [[Oran Juice Jones]] at [[Tommy Boy Records]]<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Miles Marshall |title=[INTERVIEW] Jody Watley: Pop\u2019s Fashionista Godmother |url=https://www.ebony.com/entertainment/interview-jody-watley/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=EBONY |date=22 July 2016}}</ref> and performed on tour with [[Puff Daddy]] and [[Lil' Kim]].<ref name=\"LSJPuff\">{{cite news |title=Puff Daddy leads diverse evening |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209576/p_1e/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=Lansing State Journal}}</ref> The next year, [[Spike Lee]] offered Watley a role in ''[[He Got Game]]'' - as a prostitute - a role she declined because she did not want to play a sex worker.<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> Watley was featured in the British documentary ''Glamour Girlz'' on [[Channel 4]], which documents Black women in the adult film industry. Watley was featured in the show alongside [[Charmaine Sinclair]], who had relocated to Los Angeles from London to further her career, and porn legend [[Ron Jeremy]]. In the series, Watley helps Sinclair expand her career into the adult film industry. Watley also discusses her desire to move into music, and is seen meeting by phone with [[Luther Campbell]] of [[2 Live Crew]] to discuss prospects.<ref name=\"IrishTimes\">{{cite news |title=Bachelor bliss in drumlin country |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/bachelor-bliss-in-drumlin-country-1.222655 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=5 December 1998 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"GlamourGirlz\">{{cite news |title=Glamour Girlz |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209593/the_guardian_p_93_the_guide/ |date= 28 November 1998|accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=The Guardian |department=The Guide |page=93 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1999, she had one track entitled ''5-10-15-20'', which she wrote on the ''[[Porn to Rock]]'' compilation, which was released on [[Tommy Boy Records]].<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=\"OReilly\"/> The single features [[Oran Juice Jones]]. In an interview with the ''[[National Post]]'', Watley said that she was pursuing a career in hip hop by using her fame as a porn star. Then ''National Post'' music critic [[Finbarr O'Reilly]] called Watley's single on the compilation \"one of the better tracks.\"<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> To support the compilation, Watley toured with fellow porn performers Madison Stone, Johnny Toxic, and Nina Whett, including performing at [[South by Southwest]].<ref name=\"Whyte\">{{cite news |last1=Whyte |first1=Chris |title=Savor the sweet sounds of smut |url=https://dailytitan.com/1999/03/savorthesweetsoundsofsmut/ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Titan]] |date=25 March 1999}}</ref> That same year, [[Kid Rock]] produced the track ''F.M.A.'' for the ''Deep Porn'' compilation with Midori on vocals. The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' described the single as \"moaning unprintable pillow talk over a backdrop of distorted guitars and hip-hop drums.\"<ref name=\"Berry\">{{cite news |last1=Berry |first1=Jahna |title=Wyclef Jean Raps With The Rock On Second Solo Album |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1123246/wyclef-jean-raps-with-the-rock-on-second-solo-album/ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=MTV News |date=18 August 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"Guzman\">{{cite news |last1=Guzman |first1=Isaac |title=RUDE, CRUDE AND PROUD OF IT Why a new crop of rock stars is sleazing it up |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/rude-crude-proud-new-crop-rock-stars-sleazing-article-1.881496 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=New York Daily News |date=13 August 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913062534/https://www.nydailynews.com/rude-crude-proud-new-crop-rock-stars-sleazing-article-1.881496 |archivedate=13 September 2016}}</ref> She also appeared on the cover of [[Eminem]] and [[Royce da 5'9\"]]'s side project [[Bad Meets Evil]]'s single \"[[Nuttin' to Do]]\".<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=\"GBPG\">{{cite news |title=Releaseds This Week |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209645/more2go_green_bay_pressgazette/ |date=20 July 2000 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=Green Bay Press-Gazette |department=More2go}}</ref> Watley has a second track, \"Zap\", produced by Wide (a duo consisting of Liquid Todd and [[Dr. Luke]]).<ref>[https://allhiphop.com/2000/08/01/hip-hop-meets-porn/ Hip-Hop Meets Porn! By Mike Winslow] 2000-08-01, [[AllHipHop]]</ref> Watley credits [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Lil' Kim]] as opening the door for sex positive performers, and sex workers, to perform music in mainstream entertainment.<ref name=\"OReilly\"/><ref name=\"Inc.1999\">{{cite book|author=CMJ Network, Inc.|title=CMJ New Music Monthly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA79|date=July 1999|publisher=CMJ Network, Inc.|pages=79\u2013|id=}}</ref> \n\nWatley appeared on the cover of [[Andrew Dice Clay]]'s album ''[[Face Down, Ass Up]]'' in 2000. She also released her first album, the dance LP ''Midori (AKA) Michele Watley''.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=Blender/> In 2001, she won the \"Best Supporting Actress\" video award at the [[AVN Awards]], making her the first African-American woman to ever since an AVN award.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> That same year, she released the [[rap]] album ''Miss Judged'', which featured [[rapper]] [[AMG (rapper)|AMG]]<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/> In 2001, she appeared in the video for [[Coo Coo Cal]]'s \"My Projects.\"<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/> She toured internationally for her music, including New Zealand and Europe.<ref name=\"AdultFYI\">{{cite web |title=Conversations with Midori |url=http://www.adultfyi.com/conversations-with-midori-final/ |website=AdultFYI |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> She starred in the Polish porn ''Big Sister'' and toured Poland.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\" /><ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/> Watley appeared as singer and MC on wrapper Warrior's single \"Who's Hustlin' Who\" in 2003. Watley was described as \"decent but uninteresting\" on the single by ''Rap Reviews''.<ref name=\"Knoxx\">{{cite web |last1=Knoxx |first1=A. |title=Warrior :: The Perfect Weapon |url=http://www.rapreviews.com/2003/03/warrior-the-perfect-weapon/ |website=Rap Reviews |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Around this time, she also began exploring a comeback. During her exploration of potential roles, Watley expressed issues with being offered primarily roles for older women in porn, including as [[MILF]]s.<ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn a 1997 interview with ''Black Video Illustrated'', Watley said she was straight,<ref name=\"BVI\"/> however, in the 1998, documentary ''The Unveiling'', Watley identified as bisexual.<ref name=\"Harvey\"/> She is [[monogamous]].<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> In 1999, Watley was in a relationship with [[Kid Rock]].<ref name=Blender/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9vc4aG2dVBIC&pg=PA102|title=Honky Tonk Man|last=Norris|first=Chris|date=December 2001|work=SPIN|page=102|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTMuhxamaFEC&pg=PA124|title=Fellatio Angler Story|last=Daycart|first=Renee|date=October 2000|work=SPIN|page=124}}</ref> The relationship ended after three months, with both Rock and Watley citing Rock's busy schedule as the reason for the break up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ygXnnzAlaNQC&pg=PA96|title=Pimpin' Ain't Easy|last=Jenkins|first=Sacha|date=October 1999|work=SPIN|pages=96}}</ref> Watley discovered she was pregnant after her relationship with Rock ended, and she decided not to have the baby.<ref name=Blender/> \n\nWatley is divorced from a man she describes as a \"knucklehead.\"<ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/> Watley has a daughter.<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> \n\nWatley does not like watching pornography. It took considerable time for her family to accept that she was an adult film entertainer. She took her mother with her to an adult film award ceremony in an attempt to convince her mother that the adult film industry \"also holds formal events where people dress up in black ties and fancy dresses.\"<ref name=\"OReilly\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Ceremony\n! Result\n! Category\n! Film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''1998'''\n| [[AVN Award]]\n| {{nom}}\n|Best New Starlet<ref>{{cite book|last= Wallace|first=David Foster|author-link=David Foster Wallace|title=[[Consider the Lobster]]|isbn=0316013323|page= [https://archive.org/details/considerlobster00davi/page/36 36] |year=2007 |publisher=Back Bay Books}}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| [[NightMoves Award]]\n| {{won}}\n|Best Actress (Editor's Choice)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |title=Past Winner History |accessdate=April 4, 2015 |publisher=NightMoves |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219210715/http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |archivedate=December 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| '''1999'''\n|rowspan=3| AVN Award\n| {{nom}}\n|[[AVN Award for Female Performer of the Year|Female Performer of the Year]]<ref>{{cite journal|title= Choices|journal= 1999 AVN Awards Show Program|location= Van Nuys, CA|publisher= AVN Publications, Inc.|date=January 9, 1999}}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| '''2001'''\n| {{won}}\n|[[AVN Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress - Video]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ainews.com/Archives/Story1402.phtml|title= The AVN Awards Show a Night to Remember|accessdate= April 4, 2015|author= Steve Nelson|date= January 9, 2001|publisher= Adult Industry News}}</ref>\n|''American Booty''\n|-\n| {{nom}}\n|Best Couples Sex Scene - Video <small>(with [[Dillon Day]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avnawards.com/nominees.html |title=2001 AVN Awards Nominations List |accessdate=April 4, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010309213908/http://www.avnawards.com/nominees.html |archivedate=March 9, 2001 }}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''West Side''\n|-\n| [[XRCO Award]]\n| {{nom}}\n|Actress (Single Performance)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lukeford.com/archives/updates/010319.htm |title=XRCO Award Nominations |accessdate=August 15, 2015 |date=March 19, 2001 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020104122247/http://www.lukeford.com/archives/updates/010319.htm |archivedate=January 4, 2002 }}</ref>\n|-\n| '''2009'''\n| AVN Award\n| {{won}}\n|[[AVN Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/video/2009-AVN-Award-Winners-Announced-56551.html|title= 2009 AVN Award-Winners Announced|accessdate= April 4, 2015|author= David Sullivan|date= January 11, 2009|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n==Discography==\nAlbums:\n* 2001: ''Miss Judged'', (7 tracks)<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n* 2000: ''Midori (AKA) Michele Watley'' (5 tracks)<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n\nSingles:\n* 2003: \"Who's Hustlin' Who\" - Warrior featuring Midori<ref name=\"Knoxx\"/>\n\nAlbum appearances:\n* 2002: ''Perfect Weapon'', Warrior, \"Who's Hustlin' Who\" feat. Midori<ref name=\"Knoxx\"/>\n* 2000: ''Deep Porn'', Various Artists, \"F.M.A.\" - Kid Rock featuring Midori,<ref name=\"Guzman\"/> \"Zap\" - Wide featuring Midori\n* 1999: ''[[Porn to Rock]]'', Various Artists, \"5,10,15,20\" - Midori featuring [[Oran Juice Jones]]<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n* 1997: ''Player's Call,'' Oran \"Juice\" Jones, \"Let's Stay Together\" (featuring Midori)<ref name=\"Lewis\"/>\n[[Cover girl]]:\n* 2000: ''[[Face Down, Ass Up]]'' - [[Andrew Dice Clay]]<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=Blender/>\n* 1999: \"Nuttin' To Do,\" Bad Meets Evil (Royce/Eminem)<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n\n[[Music video]] appearances: \n* 2001: \"My Projects,\" [[Coo Coo Cal (rapper)|Coo Coo Cal]] (guest appearance)<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Miller-Young, Mireille. \"A Taste for Brown Sugar: Black Women in Pornography.\" Durham: Duke University Press. {{ISBN|0822375915}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|http://www.midorimusic.net}}\n* {{IMDb name|0585636|Midori}}\n* {{iafd name|id=Midori|gender=female|name=Midori}}\n* {{afdb name|id=53|gender=female|name=Midori}}\n* {{discogs artist|436050}}\n* [https://avn.com/porn-stars/midora-aka-midori-222119.html Midori's profile at AVN]\n__NOTOC__\n\n{{AVN Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midori}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American pornographic film actors]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:African-American female rappers]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:AVN Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American pornographic actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Midori\n| image         = Midori db.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = Michele \"Midori\" Watley in 2006\n| birth_name    = Michele Watley<ref name=\"Rodeo\">{{cite web|title=Midori Interview|url=http://www.johnrodeo.com/archives/midori.html|publisher=Johnrodeo.com|accessdate=8 November 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111135610/http://www.johnrodeo.com/archives/midori.html|archivedate=11 November 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1968|07|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], [[North Carolina]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| citizenship = United States\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Singer<br/>Dancer<br/>Model<br/>Actress\n| years_active  = 1989\u2013present\n| known_for     = First African-American woman to win an [[AVN Awards|AVN Award]]\n| notable_works = \n| relatives          = [[Jody Watley]] <small>Sister</small>\n| website = {{url|http://www.midorimusic.net}}\n}}\n\n'''Michele Watley''', better known by her stage name '''Midori''' (born July 19, 1968), is an American singer, dancer, model, actress and former [[pornographic actress]]. She was inducted into the [[AVN Hall of Fame]] in 2009.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\">{{cite web |last1=Lindemulder |first1=Janine |title=Weekendowa Bezsensja: Muzyka 18+, czyli muzyka a bran\u017ca porno (3) |url=https://esensja.pl/muzyka/publicystyka/tekst.html?id=13124&ref=ak_wj |website=Esensja |accessdate=15 January 2020|language=pl}}</ref><ref>[https://avn.com/business/articles/video/2009-avn-award-winners-announced-56551.html 2009 AVN Award-Winners Announced, by David Sullivan] January 11, 2009, [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]</ref> She was the first [[African-American]] woman to win an AVN award, when she was named \"Best Supporting Actress\" in 2001.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> Watley was also named one of the top 10 \"hottest black porn stars\" of all time by ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]'' named her \"the queen of the black hardcore market.\"<ref name=\"Complex\">{{cite web |title=The Top 50 Hottest Black Porn Stars Of All Time |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/the-top-50-hottest-black-porn-stars/midori |website=Complex |accessdate=12 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Judah\">{{cite news |last1=Judah |first1=Hettie |title=Interview: Charmaine Sinclair - All glammed out and nowhere to go |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/interview-charmaine-sinclair-all-glammed-out-and-nowhere-to-go-1187977.html |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=The Independent |date=29 November 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622132025/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/interview-charmaine-sinclair-all-glammed-out-and-nowhere-to-go-1187977.html |archivedate=22 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\n\nMichele Watley was born in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. Watley has a brother and a sister. Her sister is [[Jody Watley]]. When Watley was a [[toddler]], her family relocated to [[Kansas City, Missouri]], followed by [[Chicago, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> Her grandfather and father were a ministers.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/><ref name=\"BVI\">\"Makin' It With Midori\". ''Black Video Illustrated'' (10). 1997.</ref><ref name=\"OReilly\">{{cite news |last1=O'Reilly |first1=Finbarr |title=She sings, too |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209551/p_b5/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=The National Post |language=en}}</ref> Her parents divorced when she was twelve, and Watley and her sister, Jody, moved to California. Watley called her childhood \"sheltered\" and that her parent's were \"strict.\" When she was in junior high school, she said she was \"mortified\" seeing girls kissing their boyfriends. Eventually, Watley turned into what she called \"a wild child.\"<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>\n\nAs a teenager, Watley started dancing, performing hip hop, ballet and jazz styles. She studied theater in college and performed in plays.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> As a young adult, she lived in England for nine months and in 1986, she attended dance school in France.<ref name=\"BVI\"/> Watley was also a hair model for [[Vidal Sassoon]], as well as a [[backup singer]] and dancer. As Michele Watley, she acted in commercials and modeled in ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]''. She did not pursue modeling full time, as she was \"not tall enough to be a super model.\"<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>\n\n==Career==\nShe appeared as Michele Watley in [[John Landis]]' classic comedy film starring [[Eddie Murphy]], ''[[Coming to America]]'' (1989), as one of the nude bathroom maidens.<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite news |title=Rock's Most Embarassing Siblings |url=https://www.retrojunk.com/community/post/index/46055 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |issue=41 |date=October 2005 |page=58 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter her role in ''Coming to America'', she changed her stage name to Midori.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/> She worked as an [[exotic dancer]] for four years<ref name=\"BVI\"/> and in 1995<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> she started performing in [[hardcore pornography]]. Her first scene was with [[Jake Steed]].<ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/> She didn't perform in films another year.<ref name=Blender/> Watley's rationale for entering the adult film industry was to increase the representation of women of color in the industry, which has historically been white.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/><ref name=\"OReilly\"/>\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = \"You have the playboy blond, who is sexy and every man's dream, and as an African American woman I was like 'ok, where is the sex symbol that looks like me?' And there were very few, if not any. That made me a little head strong, and I tried to figure out why. And the further I looked into it I thought 'I want to change this, because this isn't right.\"|author = Michele \"Midori\" Watley|source = 2002 interview with John Rodeo<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/>|width = 50%|align = right}}\n\nIn the 1990s, Watley began directing pornographic films<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite news |title=Watley's Porn-Again Sister |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30760348/daily_news/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=New York Daily News |date=20 February 1997}}</ref> and started back up singing,<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> including for [[Kid Rock]] in 1999.<ref name=Blender/> She initially tried to avoid appearing in [[Stereotypes of African Americans|stereotypical Black]] themed films and early in her career was mostly featured in [[interracial]] scenes in white produced films. Watley eventually started working with Black male performers because \"didn't want to have Black guys thinking I didn't do them too.\"<ref name=\"TVV\">{{cite news |last1=Suggs |first1=Donald |title=Sex Sells |publisher=The Village Voice |date=21 October 1997 |page=40 |quote=Performers who can't-or won't-cultivate the requisite image end up in a rut of \"amateur\" or low-budget race productions, where they earn as little as $200 a film. \"I didn't want to do any Soul Train booty movies,\" says 29-year-old Midori, aXa the \"Black Barbie Doll;' explaining why she initially didn't pursue Black porn films. \"Those aren't the ones getting adult awards or attention from the mainstream media;' says Midori, who received the Best Newcomer Award at the Atlantic City ceremony. Like most successful women of color in the industry, Midori started by doing interracial scenes in white-produced films. But in a sudden burst of racial consciousness, she went into Black porn. \"I didn't want to have Black guys thinking I didn't do them too,\" she explains.}}</ref> She became an spokesperson for the [[Free Speech Coalition]].<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> She was co-featured, as Michele, in the 1997 stripper documentary ''The Unveiling'', alongside [[Dixie Evans]] and Eldad Sahar.<ref name=\"LATimesUnveiling\">{{cite news |title='The Unveiling': Sure-Fire Subject Has Its Charms |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-03-27-ca-42382-story.html |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=27 March 1997}}</ref><ref name=\"McCluskey2007\">{{cite book|author=Audrey Thomas McCluskey|title=Frame by Frame III: A Filmography of the African Diasporan Image, 1994-2004|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5qmplifVDIC&pg=PA764|year=2007|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0-253-34829-3|page=764}}</ref><ref name=\"Harvey\">{{cite web |last1=Harvey |first1=Dennis |title=The Unveiling |url=https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/the-unveiling-1200453852/ |website=Variety |accessdate=15 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001172912/https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/the-unveiling-1200453852/ |archivedate=1 October 2016 |language=en |date=29 June 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"LAWeekly\">{{cite news |title=Documentary Days: The Unveiling |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/578490541/ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=Newspapers.com |agency=LA Weekly |date=25 September 1997}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described Watley as \"a petite African-American single mom who does an athletic pole-climbing act.\"<ref name=\"Harvey\"/> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' described Watley as being \"loaded with personality, and you hope that she fulfills her dream of moving into mainstream entertainment as a singer or actress.\"<ref name=\"LATimesUnveiling\"/>\n\nIn 1997, she recorded a duet with [[Oran Juice Jones]] at [[Tommy Boy Records]]<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Miles Marshall |title=[INTERVIEW] Jody Watley: Pop\u2019s Fashionista Godmother |url=https://www.ebony.com/entertainment/interview-jody-watley/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=EBONY |date=22 July 2016}}</ref> and performed on tour with [[Puff Daddy]] and [[Lil' Kim]].<ref name=\"LSJPuff\">{{cite news |title=Puff Daddy leads diverse evening |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209576/p_1e/ |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=Lansing State Journal}}</ref> The next year, [[Spike Lee]] offered Watley a role in ''[[He Got Game]]'' - as a prostitute - a role she declined because she did not want to play a sex worker.<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> Watley was featured in the British documentary ''Glamour Girlz'' on [[Channel 4]], which documents Black women in the adult film industry. Watley was featured in the show alongside [[Charmaine Sinclair]], who had relocated to Los Angeles from London to further her career, and porn legend [[Ron Jeremy]]. In the series, Watley helps Sinclair expand her career into the adult film industry. Watley also discusses her desire to move into music, and is seen meeting by phone with [[Luther Campbell]] of [[2 Live Crew]] to discuss prospects.<ref name=\"IrishTimes\">{{cite news |title=Bachelor bliss in drumlin country |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/bachelor-bliss-in-drumlin-country-1.222655 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=5 December 1998 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"GlamourGirlz\">{{cite news |title=Glamour Girlz |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209593/the_guardian_p_93_the_guide/ |date= 28 November 1998|accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=The Guardian |department=The Guide |page=93 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1999, she had one track entitled ''5-10-15-20'', which she wrote on the ''[[Porn to Rock]]'' compilation, which was released on [[Tommy Boy Records]].<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=\"OReilly\"/> The single features [[Oran Juice Jones]]. In an interview with the ''[[National Post]]'', Watley said that she was pursuing a career in hip hop by using her fame as a porn star. Then ''National Post'' music critic [[Finbarr O'Reilly]] called Watley's single on the compilation \"one of the better tracks.\"<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> To support the compilation, Watley toured with fellow porn performers Madison Stone, Johnny Toxic, and Nina Whett, including performing at [[South by Southwest]].<ref name=\"Whyte\">{{cite news |last1=Whyte |first1=Chris |title=Savor the sweet sounds of smut |url=https://dailytitan.com/1999/03/savorthesweetsoundsofsmut/ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=[[The Daily Titan]] |date=25 March 1999}}</ref> That same year, [[Kid Rock]] produced the track ''F.M.A.'' for the ''Deep Porn'' compilation with Midori on vocals. The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' described the single as \"moaning unprintable pillow talk over a backdrop of distorted guitars and hip-hop drums.\"<ref name=\"Berry\">{{cite news |last1=Berry |first1=Jahna |title=Wyclef Jean Raps With The Rock On Second Solo Album |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1123246/wyclef-jean-raps-with-the-rock-on-second-solo-album/ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=MTV News |date=18 August 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"Guzman\">{{cite news |last1=Guzman |first1=Isaac |title=RUDE, CRUDE AND PROUD OF IT Why a new crop of rock stars is sleazing it up |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/rude-crude-proud-new-crop-rock-stars-sleazing-article-1.881496 |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=New York Daily News |date=13 August 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913062534/https://www.nydailynews.com/rude-crude-proud-new-crop-rock-stars-sleazing-article-1.881496 |archivedate=13 September 2016}}</ref> She also appeared on the cover of [[Eminem]] and [[Royce da 5'9\"]]'s side project [[Bad Meets Evil]]'s single \"[[Nuttin' to Do]]\".<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=\"GBPG\">{{cite news |title=Releaseds This Week |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42209645/more2go_green_bay_pressgazette/ |date=20 July 2000 |accessdate=12 January 2020 |via=Newspapers.com |work=Green Bay Press-Gazette |department=More2go}}</ref> Watley has a second track, \"Zap\", produced by Wide (a duo consisting of Liquid Todd and [[Dr. Luke]]).<ref>[https://allhiphop.com/2000/08/01/hip-hop-meets-porn/ Hip-Hop Meets Porn! By Mike Winslow] 2000-08-01, [[AllHipHop]]</ref> Watley credits [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Lil' Kim]] as opening the door for sex positive performers, and sex workers, to perform music in mainstream entertainment.<ref name=\"OReilly\"/><ref name=\"Inc.1999\">{{cite book|author=CMJ Network, Inc.|title=CMJ New Music Monthly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA79|date=July 1999|publisher=CMJ Network, Inc.|pages=79\u2013|id=}}</ref> \n\nWatley appeared on the cover of [[Andrew Dice Clay]]'s album ''[[Face Down, Ass Up]]'' in 2000. She also released her first album, the dance LP ''Midori (AKA) Michele Watley''.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref name=Blender/> In 2001, she won the \"Best Supporting Actress\" video award at the [[AVN Awards]], making her the first African-American woman to ever since an AVN award.<ref name=\"Rodeo\"/> That same year, she released the [[rap]] album ''Miss Judged'', which featured [[rapper]] [[AMG (rapper)|AMG]]<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/> In 2001, she appeared in the video for [[Coo Coo Cal]]'s \"My Projects.\"<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/> She toured internationally for her music, including New Zealand and Europe.<ref name=\"AdultFYI\">{{cite web |title=Conversations with Midori |url=http://www.adultfyi.com/conversations-with-midori-final/ |website=AdultFYI |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref> She starred in the Polish porn ''Big Sister'' and toured Poland.<ref name=\"Lindemulder\" /><ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/> Watley appeared as singer and MC on wrapper Warrior's single \"Who's Hustlin' Who\" in 2003. Watley was described as \"decent but uninteresting\" on the single by ''Rap Reviews''.<ref name=\"Knoxx\">{{cite web |last1=Knoxx |first1=A. |title=Warrior :: The Perfect Weapon |url=http://www.rapreviews.com/2003/03/warrior-the-perfect-weapon/ |website=Rap Reviews |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Around this time, she also began exploring a comeback. During her exploration of potential roles, Watley expressed issues with being offered primarily roles for older women in porn, including as [[MILF]]s.<ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn a 1997 interview with ''Black Video Illustrated'', Watley said she was straight,<ref name=\"BVI\"/> however, in the 1998, documentary ''The Unveiling'', Watley identified as bisexual.<ref name=\"Harvey\"/> She is [[monogamous]].<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> In 1999, Watley was in a relationship with [[Kid Rock]].<ref name=Blender/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9vc4aG2dVBIC&pg=PA102|title=Honky Tonk Man|last=Norris|first=Chris|date=December 2001|work=SPIN|page=102|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTMuhxamaFEC&pg=PA124|title=Fellatio Angler Story|last=Daycart|first=Renee|date=October 2000|work=SPIN|page=124}}</ref> The relationship ended after three months, with both Rock and Watley citing Rock's busy schedule as the reason for the break up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ygXnnzAlaNQC&pg=PA96|title=Pimpin' Ain't Easy|last=Jenkins|first=Sacha|date=October 1999|work=SPIN|pages=96}}</ref> Watley discovered she was pregnant after her relationship with Rock ended, and she decided not to have the baby.<ref name=Blender/> \n\nWatley is divorced from a man she describes as a \"knucklehead.\"<ref name=\"AdultFYI\"/> Watley has a daughter.<ref name=\"OReilly\"/> \n\nWatley does not like watching pornography. It took considerable time for her family to accept that she was an adult film entertainer. She took her mother with her to an adult film award ceremony in an attempt to convince her mother that the adult film industry \"also holds formal events where people dress up in black ties and fancy dresses.\"<ref name=\"OReilly\"/>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Ceremony\n! Result\n! Category\n! Film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''1998'''\n| [[AVN Award]]\n| {{nom}}\n|Best New Starlet<ref>{{cite book|last= Wallace|first=David Foster|author-link=David Foster Wallace|title=[[Consider the Lobster]]|isbn=0316013323|page= [https://archive.org/details/considerlobster00davi/page/36 36] |year=2007 |publisher=Back Bay Books}}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| [[NightMoves Award]]\n| {{won}}\n|Best Actress (Editor\u2019s Choice)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |title=Past Winner History |accessdate=April 4, 2015 |publisher=NightMoves |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219210715/http://nightmovesusa.com/awards-show/past-winner-history.html |archivedate=December 19, 2013 }}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| '''1999'''\n|rowspan=3| AVN Award\n| {{nom}}\n|[[AVN Award for Female Performer of the Year|Female Performer of the Year]]<ref>{{cite journal|title= Choices|journal= 1999 AVN Awards Show Program|location= Van Nuys, CA|publisher= AVN Publications, Inc.|date=January 9, 1999}}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| '''2001'''\n| {{won}}\n|[[AVN Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress - Video]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ainews.com/Archives/Story1402.phtml|title= The AVN Awards Show a Night to Remember|accessdate= April 4, 2015|author= Steve Nelson|date= January 9, 2001|publisher= Adult Industry News}}</ref>\n|''American Booty''\n|-\n| {{nom}}\n|Best Couples Sex Scene - Video <small>(with [[Dillon Day]])</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avnawards.com/nominees.html |title=2001 AVN Awards Nominations List |accessdate=April 4, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010309213908/http://www.avnawards.com/nominees.html |archivedate=March 9, 2001 }}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''West Side''\n|-\n| [[XRCO Award]]\n| {{nom}}\n|Actress (Single Performance)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lukeford.com/archives/updates/010319.htm |title=XRCO Award Nominations |accessdate=August 15, 2015 |date=March 19, 2001 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020104122247/http://www.lukeford.com/archives/updates/010319.htm |archivedate=January 4, 2002 }}</ref>\n|-\n| '''2009'''\n| AVN Award\n| {{won}}\n|[[AVN Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://business.avn.com/articles/video/2009-AVN-Award-Winners-Announced-56551.html|title= 2009 AVN Award-Winners Announced|accessdate= April 4, 2015|author= David Sullivan|date= January 11, 2009|magazine= [[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]}}</ref>\n| {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n==Discography==\nAlbums:\n* 2001: ''Miss Judged'', (7 tracks)<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n* 2000: ''Midori (AKA) Michele Watley'' (5 tracks)<ref name=\"Lindemulder\"/>\n\nSingles:\n* 2003: \"Who's Hustlin' Who\" - Warrior featuring Midori<ref name=\"Knoxx\"/>\n\nAlbum appearances:\n* 2002: ''Perfect Weapon'', Warrior, \"Who's Hustlin' Who\" feat. Midori<ref name=\"Knoxx\"/>\n* 2000: ''Deep Porn'', Various Artists, \"F.M.A.\" - Kid Rock featuring Midori,<ref name=\"Guzman\"/> \"Zap\" - Wide featuring Midori\n* 1999: ''[[Porn to Rock]]'', Various Artists, \"5,10,