{"title_page": "Candida Royalle", "text_new": "{{short description|American producer, director, sex educator, feminist, and actress}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox adult biography\n| name            = Candida Royalle\n| image           = CineKink NYC 2013 Candida Royalle.jpg\n| caption         = Royalle at the 2013 CineKink awards\n| alt             = Candida Royalle at the 2013 CineKink awards\n| birth_name      = Candice Marion Vadala\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|mf=yes|1950|10|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|2015|09|07|1950|10|15}}\n| death_place     = [[Mattituck, New York]], U.S.\n| spouse          =\n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=3}}\n| alias           = Candace Chambers, Candice Ball, Candice Chambers, Candida Royalle\n| number_of_films = 74 films and 17 as director\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.candidaroyalle.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Candida Royalle''' (October 15, 1950 \u2013 September 7, 2015) was an American producer and director of couples-oriented pornography, a [[sex educator]], [[Sex-positive feminism|sex-positive feminist]], and [[pornographic actress]]. She was a member of the [[XRCO]] and the [[AVN Hall of Fame|AVN Halls of Fame]].<ref name=XRCO>{{cite web|title=XRCO Hall of Fame|url=http://www.dirtybob.com/xrco/hall.htm|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=AVNHall>{{cite web|title=AVN Hall of Fame |url=http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php |publisher=Adult Video News |accessdate=September 8, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415212412/http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php |archivedate=April 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRoyalle was born on October 15, 1950, in New York City as '''Candice Marion Vadala'''.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web|last1=Robets|first1=Sam|title=Candida Royalle, Who Made Erotic Films for Women, Dies at 64|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/11/movies/candida-royalle-maker-of-x-rated-films-dies-at-64.html|website=New York Times|accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref> Initially trained in music, dance, and art in [[New York City]], with studies at the [[High School of Art and Design]], [[Parsons School of Design]] and the [[City University of New York]].<ref name=nydnEV/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from Parsons School of Design, she began performing with the avant-garde theater group [[The Cockettes]] and in 1975 played [[Divine (performer)|Divine's]] daughter in the play ''The Heartbreak of Psoriasis''.<ref name=\"SFE\">{{cite news |last1=Stanley |first1=John |title=Film Maker Gives Erotica A Woman's Point of View |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29981663/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |publisher=San Francisco Examiner |date=21 February 1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Alilunas |first1=Peter |title=Smutty Little Movies: The Creation and Regulation of Adult Video |date=2016 |publisher=Univ of California Press |isbn=9780520291706 |page=132 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jpUkDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA132&dq=candida+royalle+cockettes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdl6Wvg6PhAhVF_4MKHfL2AH4Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=candida%20royalle%20cockettes&f=false |accessdate=27 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"SFE1975\">{{cite news |last1=Eichelbaum |first1=Stanley |title=A musical comedy that's sheer agony |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29981342/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |newspaper=San Francisco Examiner |date=20 June 1975}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975 she began her career in porn as a performer<ref name=iafd>{{cite web|title=Candida Royalle iafd bio|url=http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=Royalle/gender=female|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> appearing in about 25 movies before retiring in 1980 with ''Blue Magic'', which she also wrote.<ref name=faqs>{{cite web|title=Candida Royalle|url=http://candidaroyalle.com/blog/faqs/|accessdate=September 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910123245/http://candidaroyalle.com/blog/faqs/|archive-date=September 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nShe wrote regular columns for [[Pornographic magazine|adult magazines]] [[High Society (magazine)|High Society]] and Cheri.<ref name=AVNNYS>{{cite web|last1=Lyon|first1=Jason|title=New York Stories: The Adult Industry's Past \u2026 and Present|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/video/New-York-Stories-The-Adult-Industry-s-Past-and-Present-597244.html|publisher=Adult Video News|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Royalle founded [[Femme Productions]], with the goal of making erotica based on female desire, as well as pornographic films aimed at helping couple therapy. Her productions are aimed more to women and couples than to the standard pornographic audience of men, and have been praised by counselors and therapists for depicting healthy and realistic sexual activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alh.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/citation/2/4/784|title=Discourses of Desire: Liberals, Feminists, and the Politics of Pornography in the 1980s -- Cameron 2 (4): 784 -- American Literary History|publisher=alh.oxfordjournals.org|accessdate=January 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\nRoyalle stated that she tried to avoid \"[[misogynous]] predictability\", and depiction of sex in \"\u2026as grotesque and graphic [a way] as possible.\" She also criticized the male-centredness of the typical pornographic film, in which scenes end when the male actor ejaculates. Royalle's films are not \u201cgoal oriented\u201d towards a final \"[[cum shot]]\"; instead, her films depict sexual activity within the broader context of women's emotional and social lives.<ref>illy Bragge, [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/06/15/1087244912619.html \"Girls on top\"], ''[[The Age]]'', June 16, 2004.</ref> In 1989, she signed the Post Porn Modernist Manifesto.<ref>[http://www.google.com/search?q=cache:XeNo-2FP96QJ:www.sexuality.org/l/art/anniems.html+%22Post+Porn+Modernist+Manifesto%22&hl=en&gl=uk&ct=clnk&cd=7 15 Worst Pick Up Lines You've Ever Heard In Hindi - Enjoy The Rainny Romance],{{https://www.bgsraw.in/2019/05/15-worst-pick-up-lines-youve-ever-heardin-hindi-translate-enjoy-the-rainny-romance.html|date=May 2019}} google.com; accessed May 28, 2019.</ref>\n\nShe was also a public speaker, giving lectures at [[Smithsonian Institution]], the World Congress on Sexology and numerous universities and professional conferences.<ref name=AVNObit/>\n\nIn 2004, she authored the book ''How to Tell a Naked Man What to Do''.<ref name=AVNObit/>\n\nA 5-track EP titled ''Candida Cosmica'', a collaboration between Royalle and [[Patrick Cowley]] from the mid 70s, was released in October 2016 by Dark Entries Records.<ref name=EP>{{cite web|last1=Lefebvre|first1=Sam|title=Waking the Spirit of a Disco Innovator|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/07/arts/music/patrick-cowley-disco-reissues.html|publisher=NY Times|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''Candice'' a documentary about Royalle's life and finding out what happened to her mother who left her as a child, was screened at various documentary film festivals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gee |first1=Dana |title=Godmother of feminist porn is focus of new doc Candice {{!}} Vancouver Sun |url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/movies/godmother-of-feminist-porn-is-focus-of-new-doc-candice |accessdate=22 May 2019 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=26 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shepherd |first1=Jeremy |title=Doc examines life of adult film star turned feminist icon |url=https://www.nsnews.com/entertainment/film/doc-examines-life-of-adult-film-star-turned-feminist-icon-1.23810935 |accessdate=22 May 2019 |publisher=North Shore News |date=3 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lamble |first1=David |title=What's up, DocFest? |url=https://www.ebar.com/arts_&_culture/movies//276509 |accessdate=22 May 2019 |work=The Bay Area Reporter |publisher=The Bay Area Reporter |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nRoyalle was a member of the [[American Association of Sex Educators, Counselors and Therapists]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zeiss Stange|title=The Multimedia Encyclopedia of Women in Today's World|first1=Mary|last2=Oyster|first2=Carol K.|last3=Sloan|first3=Jane E.|date=2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=9781452270685|page=291|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PTMTBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291&dq=American+Association+of+Sex+Educators,+Counselors+and+Therapists+Candida+Royalle&source=bl&ots=xikxj72xt2&sig=dNVkacekz_iuPpCro873KXCdb2I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBmoVChMI37G89cfmxwIVi20-Ch0GCg3y#v=onepage&q=American%20Association%20of%20Sex%20Educators%2C%20Counselors%20and%20Therapists%20Candida%20Royalle&f=false}}</ref> and a founding board-member of [[Feminists for Free Expression]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Denfeld|first1=Rene|title=The New Victorians|date=2009|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=9780446565233|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g0xZenCvYcoC&pg=PT98&lpg=PT98&dq=Feminists+for+Free+Expression+Candida+Royalle&source=bl&ots=41wCOJz2bm&sig=dAlRI35v3cWmnWCJMXA5gW_5Cnk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCwQ6AEwA2oVChMIjq3qi8jmxwIVRDg-Ch0bSg7y#v=onepage&q=Feminists%20for%20Free%20Expression%20Candida%20Royalle&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nIn the 1980s, she was married to producer Per Sjostedt.<ref name=\"per\">{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Linda|title=Hard Core: Power, Pleasure, and the \"frenzy of the Visible\"|date=1989|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=0520066529|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hardcore00will/page/n263 246]\u2013247|url=https://archive.org/details/hardcore00will|url-access=registration|quote=Per Sjostedt candida.|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref> In May 2006, Royalle announced that she was engaged to be married.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eros-ny.com/articles/2006-05-16/candida_royalle0516/|title=Candida Royalle|accessdate=May 26, 2007|author=Abby Ehmann|date=May 16, 2006|publisher=Eros NY|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061117073501/http://eros-ny.com/articles/2006-05-16/candida_royalle0516|archivedate=November 17, 2006}}</ref> She died in [[Mattituck, New York]]<ref name=AVNObit>{{cite web|last1=Kernes|first1=Mark|title=Famed Actress/Director Candida Royalle Passes|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/video/Famed-Actress-Director-Candida-Royalle-Passes-606042.html|website=avn.com|publisher=Adult Video News|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> on September 7, 2015, aged 64, from [[ovarian cancer]].<ref name=nydnEV>{{cite news|last1=Vanmetre|first1=Elizabeth|title=Former porn star turned director Candida Royalle dies at age 64|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/candida-royalle-dies-age-64-article-1.2351467|accessdate=September 8, 2015|work=New York Daily News|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nypost>{{cite web|last1=Celona|first1=Larry|title=Orphaned ex-porn star dies of cancer|url=https://nypost.com/2015/09/07/orphaned-ex-porn-star-dies-of-cancer|website=New York Post|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.candidaroyalle.com/ Candida Royalle's Website]\n* {{IMDb name|0747263|Candida Royalle}}\n* {{iafd name|id=Royalle|gender=female|name=Candida Royalle}}\n* {{afdb name|id=5058|gender=female|name=Candida Royalle}}\n* {{findagrave|152008545}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royalle, Candida}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women pornographic film directors]]\n[[Category:Feminist pornography]]\n[[Category:Sex-positive feminists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from ovarian cancer]]\n[[Category:Parsons School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:City University of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:High School of Art and Design alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American producer, director, sex educator, feminist, and actress}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox adult biography\n| name            = Candida Royalle\n| image           = CineKink NYC 2013 Candida Royalle.jpg\n| caption         = Royalle at the 2013 CineKink awards\n| alt             = Candida Royalle at the 2013 CineKink awards\n| birth_name      = Candice Marion Vadala\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|mf=yes|1950|10|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|2015|09|07|1950|10|15}}\n| death_place     = [[Mattituck, New York]], U.S.\n| spouse          =\n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=3}}\n| alias           = Candace Chambers, Candice Ball, Candice Chambers, Candida Royalle\n| number_of_films = 74 films and 17 as director\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.candidaroyalle.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Candida Royalle''' (October 15, 1950 \u2013 September 7, 2015) was an American producer and director of couples-oriented pornography, a [[sex educator]], [[Sex-positive feminism|sex-positive feminist]], and [[pornographic actress]]. She was a member of the [[XRCO]] and the [[AVN Hall of Fame|AVN Halls of Fame]].<ref name=XRCO>{{cite web|title=XRCO Hall of Fame|url=http://www.dirtybob.com/xrco/hall.htm|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=AVNHall>{{cite web|title=AVN Hall of Fame |url=http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php |publisher=Adult Video News |accessdate=September 8, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415212412/http://www.avnawards.com/halloffame.php |archivedate=April 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRoyalle was born on October 15, 1950, in New York City as '''Candice Marion Vadala'''.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web|last1=Robets|first1=Sam|title=Candida Royalle, Who Made Erotic Films for Women, Dies at 64|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/11/movies/candida-royalle-maker-of-x-rated-films-dies-at-64.html|website=New York Times|accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref> Initially trained in music, dance, and art in [[New York City]], with studies at the [[High School of Art and Design]], [[Parsons School of Design]] and the [[City University of New York]].<ref name=nydnEV/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from Parsons School of Design, she began performing with the avant-garde theater group [[The Cockettes]] and in 1975 played [[Divine (performer)|Divine's]] daughter in the play ''The Heartbreak of Psoriasis''.<ref name=\"SFE\">{{cite news |last1=Stanley |first1=John |title=Film Maker Gives Erotica A Woman's Point of View |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29981663/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |publisher=San Francisco Examiner |date=21 February 1988}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Alilunas |first1=Peter |title=Smutty Little Movies: The Creation and Regulation of Adult Video |date=2016 |publisher=Univ of California Press |isbn=9780520291706 |page=132 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jpUkDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA132&dq=candida+royalle+cockettes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdl6Wvg6PhAhVF_4MKHfL2AH4Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=candida%20royalle%20cockettes&f=false |accessdate=27 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"SFE1975\">{{cite news |last1=Eichelbaum |first1=Stanley |title=A musical comedy that's sheer agony |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29981342/ |accessdate=27 March 2019 |newspaper=San Francisco Examiner |date=20 June 1975}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975 she began her career in porn as a performer<ref name=iafd>{{cite web|title=Candida Royalle iafd bio|url=http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=Royalle/gender=female|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> appearing in about 25 movies before retiring in 1980 with ''Blue Magic'', which she also wrote.<ref name=faqs>{{cite web|title=Candida Royalle|url=http://candidaroyalle.com/blog/faqs/|accessdate=September 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910123245/http://candidaroyalle.com/blog/faqs/|archive-date=September 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nShe wrote regular columns for [[Pornographic magazine|adult magazines]] [[High Society (magazine)|High Society]] and Cheri.<ref name=AVNNYS>{{cite web|last1=Lyon|first1=Jason|title=New York Stories: The Adult Industry's Past \u2026 and Present|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/video/New-York-Stories-The-Adult-Industry-s-Past-and-Present-597244.html|publisher=Adult Video News|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Royalle founded [[Femme Productions]], with the goal of making erotica based on female desire, as well as pornographic films aimed at helping couple therapy. Her productions are aimed more to women and couples than to the standard pornographic audience of men, and have been praised by counselors and therapists for depicting healthy and realistic sexual activity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alh.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/citation/2/4/784|title=Discourses of Desire: Liberals, Feminists, and the Politics of Pornography in the 1980s -- Cameron 2 (4): 784 -- American Literary History|publisher=alh.oxfordjournals.org|accessdate=January 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\nRoyalle stated that she tried to avoid \"[[misogynous]] predictability\", and depiction of sex in \"\u2026as grotesque and graphic [a way] as possible.\" She also criticized the male-centredness of the typical pornographic film, in which scenes end when the male actor ejaculates. Royalle\u2019s films are not \u201cgoal oriented\u201d towards a final \"[[cum shot]]\"; instead, her films depict sexual activity within the broader context of women's emotional and social lives.<ref>illy Bragge, [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/06/15/1087244912619.html \"Girls on top\"], ''[[The Age]]'', June 16, 2004.</ref> In 1989, she signed the Post Porn Modernist Manifesto.<ref>[http://www.google.com/search?q=cache:XeNo-2FP96QJ:www.sexuality.org/l/art/anniems.html+%22Post+Porn+Modernist+Manifesto%22&hl=en&gl=uk&ct=clnk&cd=7 15 Worst Pick Up Lines You've Ever Heard In Hindi - Enjoy The Rainny Romance],{{https://www.bgsraw.in/2019/05/15-worst-pick-up-lines-youve-ever-heardin-hindi-translate-enjoy-the-rainny-romance.html|date=May 2019}} google.com; accessed May 28, 2019.</ref>\n\nShe was also a public speaker, giving lectures at [[Smithsonian Institution]], the World Congress on Sexology and numerous universities and professional conferences.<ref name=AVNObit/>\n\nIn 2004, she authored the book ''How to Tell a Naked Man What to Do''.<ref name=AVNObit/>\n\nA 5-track EP titled ''Candida Cosmica'', a collaboration between Royalle and [[Patrick Cowley]] from the mid 70s, was released in October 2016 by Dark Entries Records.<ref name=EP>{{cite web|last1=Lefebvre|first1=Sam|title=Waking the Spirit of a Disco Innovator|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/07/arts/music/patrick-cowley-disco-reissues.html|publisher=NY Times|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''Candice'' a documentary about Royalle's life and finding out what happened to her mother who left her as a child, was screened at various documentary film festivals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gee |first1=Dana |title=Godmother of feminist porn is focus of new doc Candice {{!}} Vancouver Sun |url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/movies/godmother-of-feminist-porn-is-focus-of-new-doc-candice |accessdate=22 May 2019 |publisher=Vancouver Sun |date=26 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shepherd |first1=Jeremy |title=Doc examines life of adult film star turned feminist icon |url=https://www.nsnews.com/entertainment/film/doc-examines-life-of-adult-film-star-turned-feminist-icon-1.23810935 |accessdate=22 May 2019 |publisher=North Shore News |date=3 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lamble |first1=David |title=What's up, DocFest? |url=https://www.ebar.com/arts_&_culture/movies//276509 |accessdate=22 May 2019 |work=The Bay Area Reporter |publisher=The Bay Area Reporter |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Affiliations==\nRoyalle was a member of the [[American Association of Sex Educators, Counselors and Therapists]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zeiss Stange|title=The Multimedia Encyclopedia of Women in Today's World|first1=Mary|last2=Oyster|first2=Carol K.|last3=Sloan|first3=Jane E.|date=2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=9781452270685|page=291|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PTMTBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291&dq=American+Association+of+Sex+Educators,+Counselors+and+Therapists+Candida+Royalle&source=bl&ots=xikxj72xt2&sig=dNVkacekz_iuPpCro873KXCdb2I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBmoVChMI37G89cfmxwIVi20-Ch0GCg3y#v=onepage&q=American%20Association%20of%20Sex%20Educators%2C%20Counselors%20and%20Therapists%20Candida%20Royalle&f=false}}</ref> and a founding board-member of [[Feminists for Free Expression]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Denfeld|first1=Rene|title=The New Victorians|date=2009|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=9780446565233|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g0xZenCvYcoC&pg=PT98&lpg=PT98&dq=Feminists+for+Free+Expression+Candida+Royalle&source=bl&ots=41wCOJz2bm&sig=dAlRI35v3cWmnWCJMXA5gW_5Cnk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCwQ6AEwA2oVChMIjq3qi8jmxwIVRDg-Ch0bSg7y#v=onepage&q=Feminists%20for%20Free%20Expression%20Candida%20Royalle&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nIn the 1980s, she was married to producer Per Sjostedt.<ref name=\"per\">{{cite book|last1=Williams|first1=Linda|title=Hard Core: Power, Pleasure, and the \"frenzy of the Visible\"|date=1989|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=0520066529|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hardcore00will/page/n263 246]\u2013247|url=https://archive.org/details/hardcore00will|url-access=registration|quote=Per Sjostedt candida.|accessdate=28 February 2016}}</ref> In May 2006, Royalle announced that she was engaged to be married.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eros-ny.com/articles/2006-05-16/candida_royalle0516/|title=Candida Royalle|accessdate=May 26, 2007|author=Abby Ehmann|date=May 16, 2006|publisher=Eros NY|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061117073501/http://eros-ny.com/articles/2006-05-16/candida_royalle0516|archivedate=November 17, 2006}}</ref> She died in [[Mattituck, New York]]<ref name=AVNObit>{{cite web|last1=Kernes|first1=Mark|title=Famed Actress/Director Candida Royalle Passes|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/video/Famed-Actress-Director-Candida-Royalle-Passes-606042.html|website=avn.com|publisher=Adult Video News|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> on September 7, 2015, aged 64, from [[ovarian cancer]].<ref name=nydnEV>{{cite news|last1=Vanmetre|first1=Elizabeth|title=Former porn star turned director Candida Royalle dies at age 64|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/candida-royalle-dies-age-64-article-1.2351467|accessdate=September 8, 2015|work=New York Daily News|date=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nypost>{{cite web|last1=Celona|first1=Larry|title=Orphaned ex-porn star dies of cancer|url=https://nypost.com/2015/09/07/orphaned-ex-porn-star-dies-of-cancer|website=New York Post|accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.candidaroyalle.com/ Candida Royalle's Website]\n* {{IMDb name|0747263|Candida Royalle}}\n* {{iafd name|id=Royalle|gender=female|name=Candida Royalle}}\n* {{afdb name|id=5058|gender=female|name=Candida Royalle}}\n* {{findagrave|152008545}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Royalle, Candida}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women pornographic film directors]]\n[[Category:Feminist pornography]]\n[[Category:Sex-positive feminists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from ovarian cancer]]\n[[Category:Parsons School of Desi